Project Nexus AI: Persistent Project Intelligence
Tagline: One Project. One Memory. Every Decision. Every Engineer.

The Problem
Software development is fragmented. Context is scattered across Jira, Slack, GitHub, and Confluence. Engineers spend 20–40% of their time searching for information, reconstructing project context, or waiting for teammates to answer repeat questions—costing organizations thousands of hours annually.

Our Solution: The Persistent Intelligence Layer
Project Nexus AI acts as the "long-term memory" of a software project. By linking engineering artifacts—tasks, code, ADRs, and discussions—into a unified Knowledge Graph, the platform enables an AI agent to reason across the entire project lifecycle.

Core Features

Single-Command Context: Use "Load Project" to instantly hydrate an AI agent with the full history and intent of a project.

Relational Memory: Unlike simple vector stores, our Knowledge Graph maps the relationships between a Jira ticket, a specific code commit, and the ADR that justified the design.

Agentic Teammate: An AI that doesn't just write code, but "remembers" the architectural decisions and trade-offs made months ago.

Business Impact

Onboarding: 30–50% faster ramp-up time for new engineers.

Efficiency: 20–40% reduction in time spent searching for project documentation.

Resilience: Drastically reduced "bus factor" by making historical decisions discoverable.

Part 2: How to Build the "Winning" Demo
To satisfy the requirement for a "working prototype" that shows AI in action, follow this "Agentic UX" blueprint.

1. The "Magic Moment" Demo Flow
Do not show login screens or settings. Start with the "Load Project" command.

The Hook: Start with a "stale" state. Show an engineer asking: "Why are we using Kafka here instead of RabbitMQ?" The current AI (or a generic bot) fails because it lacks context.

The Action: The user types /load-project Payments-Platform.

The Reveal: Show a "Hydration" UI (a progress bar or a quick dashboard) showing the agent pulling in Jira tickets, Git commits, and ADRs.

The Payoff: Ask the same question again. Now, the agent provides a detailed answer: "We moved to Kafka in June 2025 to handle high-throughput event streaming, as documented in ADR-042 and discussed in the #arch-payments Slack thread."

2. Technical Implementation Strategy
The Knowledge Graph: You don't need a massive enterprise database. Use SQLite with a few tables representing your core entities (Artifacts, Decisions, Links). To the AI, this is the graph.

Agent Logic (The "Brain"): Use a framework like LangChain or simple OpenAI/Anthropic API calls. The agent should:

Observe the user query.

Use a "Tool" (a simple SQL query function) to fetch relevant nodes/relationships from your SQLite DB.

Reason about the context to provide the answer.

Keep it Simple: Focus on the provenance—the AI must cite its source (e.g., "Source: ADR-042"). This is the most impressive part of a demo.

3. Winning Tips for the Pitch
Human Voiceover: Do not use AI-generated voiceovers for your demo video or presentation. Your passion and explanation of the "why" are crucial for judges.

The "Vibe" Coding: Use tools like Cursor or Windsurf to build your prototype fast. Spend your time on the integration (connecting the Jira API/Mock and Git data) rather than on perfect UI design.

The Evaluation Rubric: Judges will look for "Task Completion Rate" and "Tool-Use Accuracy". Ensure your demo shows the agent actually using a tool (fetching data) rather than just hallucinating a smart answer.
